SI 544 FA 2020: Problem Set #1

You were introduced to the COVID-19 Data Hub (Guidotti & Ardia, 2020) in this week’s discussion. We are going to delve a bit deeper into that data set for this assignment. We will focus on cleaning and manipulating the data so it’s suitable for generating plots to help us understand the spread of COVID-19.

Google Mobility Reports (GMR) use pooled data to report where people are. A example of a mobility report can be accessed via https://www.gstatic.com/covid19/mobility/2020-09-11_US_Mobility_Report_en.pdf. The GMR provides an indication of the percent change from baseline for the following types of locations: retail and recreation, grocery and pharmacy, parks, transit stations, workplaces, and residential. The GMR data can be joined to the COVID-19 Data Hub data set by using the gmr= option when the COVID-19 data set is loaded (see first R block below).

In addition to the GMR, the authors of the COVID-19 Data Hub have made it easy to link the COVID-19 data set with data from the World Bank. Of particular interest are two indicators: Total GDP and number of hospital beds per 1000 people. The first R block below loads country-level data including the two World Bank indicators mentioned and the second one loads province-level data for Canada (Canada’s provinces are analogous to states in the USA).

  1. Create a bar plot that shows the number of tests conducted per 1000 people for each province in Canada. Use the most up to date data as you can find using “COVID19” package. (Hint: for Canada, the administrative_area_level_2 variable contains the province name.)
# Type your code here

group_province <- canada %>%
   filter(date == "2020-09-20") %>%
   group_by(administrative_area_level_2) %>%
   select(administrative_area_level_2, population, tests) %>%
   mutate(tests_per_1000 = tests / population * 1000)

Interpret your results: overall, how are
people behaving differently with COVID-19?  How do people's behaviours
differ between Ontario and British Columbia?

Answer: More people were staying home in Ontario than in British Columbia. This is particularly apparent in the residential, workplace, and transit plots. More people in British Columbia were out at the parks at least from April - June, while more people in Ontario headed to the parks in July. Ontario shows a deeper decline in retail and grocery plots, but you can also see very similar upticks and downswings among both provinces in these plots.
